Project 2¶

Scientific Question: How does gene sequencing on CFTR of different animals reveal about the severity and the development of the mutation on the CFTR gene of humans?

Scientific Hypothesis: If humans show a difference in the CFTR gene comparing to mouse, ferrets, and pigs in the gene sequence and structure of the CFTR gene, then this suggests the reason why cystic fibrosis has a significantly larger affect on humans comparing to the other animals.

CFTR, Cystic Fibrosis Transmembrane Conductance Regulator, is the gene responsible for Cystic Fibrosis, located on chromosome 7. Cystic Fibrosis is a dysfunction of the CFTR channel from exocrine tissues caused by a mutation in the gene. The most common mutation of the CFTR gene is F508del, where a deletion of three nucleotides cause the loss of phenylalanin at the 508th position of the protein.

For the bioinformatics analysis of this topic, Multiple Sequence Alignment (MSA), Homology Modeling, Sequence logos, and Heatmap is used. The data used for MSA, Homology Modeling, and Sequence Logos are downloaded from Uniprot as individual fasta files. They were then combined into one file after alignment on Uniprot. The data used for the Heatmap is obtained from NCBI (GEO), from "Myosin 7b is a regulatory long noncoding RNA in the human heart" (GSE157217) https://www-ncbi-nlm-nih-gov.ezproxy.u-pec.fr/geo/browse/?view=series&type=3&suppl=CSV&date=01Sep2020&display=20&zsort=title, and downloaded as a csv file. The fasta files were uploaded to SWISS Modeling and pdb files of protein models obtained are used for the coding section of Homology Modeling.

Part 1: Load the Packages¶


ProDy: ProDy is a package for protein structural dynamics analysis. It parses PDB and DCD files and the protein structures. It's often used with heterogeneous X-ray structures, Blast searches, NMR models, ANM, and GNM. Heterogeneous X-ray structures are used fro missing residues and mutations, and NMR models are often essential to dynamic analysis. NMWiz can be used with the experimental datasets, simulations, and theoretical to visualize the dynamics. http://prody.csb.pitt.edu

logomaker: Logomaker is a package that generates sequence logos that illustrates properties of DNA, RNA, and protein sequneces. It makes it convenient to genearte and customize sequence logos within the programming environment. They are rendered as vector graphics embedded ithin native matplotlib Axes objects. It is compatible with both Python 2.7 and 3.6. Many web-programs, such as WebLogo, for making sequence logos are also available. https://academic.oup.com/bioinformatics/article/36/7/2272/5671693 https://logomaker.readthedocs.io/en/latest/

biotite: Biotite is for identifying homologous sequence regious and finding disulfide bonds in a protein structure. It provides tools to search and fetch data from biological databases and visualizing sequence and structure data. It also allows access to popular sequence/strucutre file formats for the analysis of editing of the data. Most of the data is stored as NumPy ndarray objects to the convenience of C-accelerated analysis and a wider usability. It allows users to skip writing code for basic functionality as a result. https://www.biotite-python.org

ipython: Ipython is an interactive Python shell that connects the code in Jupyter notebooks to otehr interactive frontends. It allows comprehensive object introspection, extensible tab completion, and session logging and reloading. The package also provide the caching of output results during a session with automatically generated references. The convenience of embeddable in other Python programs makes this package easily usable. Additionally, they also have intergrated access to the pdb debugger and the Python profiler. https://pypi.org/project/ipython/

pandas: Pandas is the package used for working with data sets, specifically with data analysis, cleaning, exploring, and manipulation. It's one of the most widely used Python package. The name came from the reference to "Panel Data" and "Python Data Analysis". It allows the analysis of large data and users to generate conclusions based on statistical theories. Not only does it clean data sets, it also makes them more readable. https://www.w3schools.com/python/pandas/pandas_intro.asp

numpy: Another widely used package, Numpy, provides N-dimensional array objects, sophisticated functions that work the C/C++, Fortran, and Python. It is also used as an efficient multi-dimensional container of generic data. The ndarray object provides many supporting functions that make ndarray easy to use. It's faster than lists because they are stored in one place in memory. They are much faster than lists and can be easily manipulated and accessed. https://www.w3schools.com/python/numpy/numpy_intro.asp

matplotlib: Matplotlib is a package that is used for interactive visualizations in Python. It allows users to create quality plots and customize visual style and layout. It also offers many file formats to export in. Additionally, it offers plotting methods and numerical mathematics extension NumPy. Other packages like SciPy also make use of Matplotlib. https://matplotlib.org https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matplotlib

Part 3: Performating Bioinformatics Analysis¶

Multiple Sequence Alignment¶

Multiple Sequence Alignment is the sequence alignment of three or more protein sequences. It often illustrates mutations as point mutations, and isertion or deletion mutations. It is used to analyze the sequence conservation of protein domains, teritary and secondary structures, and sometimes individual amino acids and nucleotides.

Homology Model¶

Homology modeling is a method that allows the comparison and prediction of two or more protein structures. It is often used for its accuracy and easiness of the method during computational structure prediction. Homology modeling is based on the idea that, "if two proteins share a high enough sequence similarity, they are likely to have very similar three-dimensional structures" https://microbenotes.com/homology-modeling-working-steps-and-uses/

In [61]:
# Homology Model of Human and Pig
# Parse the protein structures of the two models
# Global variable struct1 is the homology model of the CFTR gene of humans
# Local variable struct2 is the homology model of the CFTR gene of pigs
struct1 = parsePDB("human_model.pdb")
struct2 = parsePDB("pig_model.pdb")

# Match chains and store into 2D array called matches
matches = matchChains(struct1,struct2,seqid =90, overlap = 90)

# Code check
#print(matches)

# Calculate the RMSD of chains from both proteins
first_ca = matches[0][0]
second_ca = matches[0][1]
calcRMSD(first_ca, second_ca)

# Apply Kabsch algorithm to ensure that the strucutres are correctly aligned
calcTransformation(first_ca, second_ca).apply(first_ca);

# Run code to get the value fo RMSD
calcRMSD(first_ca, second_ca)

Heat Map¶

Heat maps are a graphical representation of data that shows clusters with colors. It is especially useful when needing a visualization of large or complex data. The yellow color is a positive z score, hence higher similarity. The blue color is a negative z score, hence lower similarity or cluster.

In [ ]:
# store the file as data
# Local variable, data, reads human's cftr gene expression
data = pd.read_csv("cftr_human1_counts.csv")

# Change the size of the subplot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(1,60))

# Chnage the center parameter and map color 
sns.heatmap(data.corr(), center = 0, cmap = "Y1GnBu")

# Set heatmap title and plot
ax.set_title("Heat Map")
plt.show()

Part 4: Analysis of the Results¶

Cystic fibrosis is known to be nonexistent in animals. After analyzing the protein sequences and the past observations of the human, mouse, ferret, and pig CFTR genes, it is concluded that the CFTR gene of humans share the most similarity with pigs, with the RMSD value of only 2.6e-14, while the other two animals shared a RMSD value of more than 10. Even though the homology model of pigs' CFTR gene is similar to the homology model of CFTR gene of humans, the analysis of sequence logo proves otherwise, especially from sequences 1170 to 1205. The sequence logo made from the multiple sequece alignment of the data from the four samples show that there are an adequate number of different residues at some locations, which suggests to be the reason why animals, unlike humans, do not get Cystic Fibrosis even though they also have the CFTR gene for the same function. The heatmap also shows that the magnitude of the mutation of the CFTR gene is mainly clustered in one area. Overall, the bioinformatics analysis of multiple sequence alignment, homology modeling, heatmap, and sequence logos make strong suggestions that the differences in the gene sequences of the four sample's perspective CFTR gene can explain the severity of Cystic Fibrosis in humans comparing to other organisms.
